The problem presented is a standard, well-posed exercise in linear anisotropic elasticity. Its claims are scientifically grounded and its structure is logical. We proceed directly to the derivation.

The constitutive relation for a linear elastic material is given by Hooke's Law. In Voigt notation, the strain vector $\{\varepsilon\}$ and stress vector $\{\sigma\}$ are related by the compliance matrix $[\mathbf{S}]$ as $\{\varepsilon\} = [\mathbf{S}] \{\sigma\}$, where $\{\sigma\} = (\sigma_{11}, \sigma_{22}, \sigma_{33}, \sigma_{23}, \sigma_{13}, \sigma_{12})^{\mathsf{T}}$ and $\{\varepsilon\} = (\varepsilon_{11}, \varepsilon_{22}, \varepsilon_{33}, \gamma_{23}, \gamma_{13}, \gamma_{12})^{\mathsf{T}}$. The engineering shear strains are defined as $\gamma_{ij} = 2\varepsilon_{ij}$ for $i 
eq j$.

For a transversely isotropic material with the $x_3$-axis as the axis of rotational symmetry, there are five independent elastic constants. The compliance matrix $[\mathbf{S}]$ has a specific structure due to this symmetry. We construct this matrix by considering elemental loading cases.

First, consider a uniaxial tensile stress $\sigma_{33}$ applied along the fiber axis, with all other stress components being zero. The resulting strains are, by definition of the engineering constants:
